This paper discusses a man-in-the-middle exploit in online communication, specifically in web-based email discourse, which falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper also focuses on the manipulation of interpersonal perception, which involves human-computer interaction (cs.HC) and natural language processing (cs.CL). The use of a malicious web browser extension also involves software engineering (cs.SE) and cybercrime (cs.CY). Finally, the paper discusses the social and psychological factors that affect online communication, which falls under the category of social and information sciences (cs.SI).
